Problem 1 - Simple Lattice Method¶

We are going to take the coordinates from Problem 6 and input them into the simple lattice method. The simple lattice method takes a planar finite wing (a flat wing with no curvature) and calculates an approximation for the 3D coefficient of lift using the geometry of the wing. We start with the above geometry for our wing. We set this geometry up in Proect 6, and now we will be running the analysis on it.

Similar to our source panel method and our vortex panel. For each panel we have:

  • A Control Point
  • Left Bound Vortex
  • Right Bound Vortex

Since we have 4 panels, we will have 4 values for the downwash. One for each panel .We have a condition that w1 = w2 = w3 = w4

These equations can get a bit complicated. We'll need to define them for both the port and starboard side of the wings. This just means the left and right wings respectively. For this method, we have to include the contributions from both sides of the wing. However, because the wing is symmetric about the y = 0 plane, the lift force acting at a point on one side of the wing is equal to that at the other side. This means we only need to calculate the circulation at one side of the wing or the affects at one side of the wing, and then assume that the same circulation/lift acts on the other side of the wing. We'll need to slightly adjust the values for our vortex points.

The big picture calculations have already been written into the code. Some steps you'll need to take to complete the code and get all of the outputs:

Our analysis will give us a 4 x 4 system of equations. The equations are seen below. The supplement provides you with the left side of the system of equations. You should try to understand how these outputs come about (generally)

$$ \begin{bmatrix} A_{1} \Gamma_{1} & A_{2} \Gamma_{2} & A_{3} \Gamma_{1} & A_{4} \Gamma_{4}\\ B_{1} \Gamma_{1} & B_{2} \Gamma_{2} & B_{3} \Gamma_{3} & B_{4} \Gamma_{4}\\ C_{1} \Gamma_{1} & C_{2} \Gamma_{2} & C_{3} \Gamma_{3} & C_{4} \Gamma_{4} \\ D_{1} \Gamma_{1} & D_{2} \Gamma_{2} & D_{3} \Gamma_{3} & D_{4} \Gamma_{4} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \end{bmatrix}$$

or

$$\begin{bmatrix} A_{1} & A_{2} & A_{3} & A_{4}\\ B_{1} & B_{2} & B_{3} & B_{4} \\ C_{1} & C_{2} & C_{3} & C_{4} \\ D_{1} & D_{2} & D_{3} & D_{4} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \Gamma_{1} \\ \Gamma_{2} \\ \Gamma_{3} \\ \Gamma_{4} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \\ -4\pi U_{\infty} \alpha \end{bmatrix}$$

Since the code provides you with the left hand side, you'll need to set up the RHS and solve the system of linear equations for $\Gamma_{1}$, $\Gamma_{2}$, $\Gamma_{3}$ and $\Gamma_{4}$. This is the value of circulation at each panel of our wing. ($\Gamma_{1}$ refers to the panel nearest the root, $\Gamma_{4}$ refers to the panel closest to the top of the wing)

After this, you'll have the circulation for each panel. You can then calculate the Coefficient of Lift at every panel, as well as the total lift of the wing. The total lift of the wing is given by the following equation that you will need to implement into the function.

$$ L = 2*\rho_{\infty}U_{\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\Gamma_{n}\Delta_{y} $$

Use this to calculate the total lift of the wing. We can also calculate the coefficient of lift for each panel using the following equation: $$C_{ln} = \frac{2\Gamma_{n}}{U_{\infty}c_{av}}$$

Where $c_{av}$ is the average chord of the wing.

The code takes inputs related to the geometry of the Wing, as well as the flight conditions of the wing. Make the following changes somewhere in your code:

  • The geometry from Project 6 is provided in inches, you should convert it to ft either before or after you pass the input to the function.
  • The speed of the plane is provided in MPH, convert this to ft/sec
  • Angle of attack is given in degrees, for this problem it needs to be converted to radians.
  • Determine rho at the correct altitude, and convert/use a density in slug/ft^3
  • Within your code you need the spacing between panels in the spanwise direction, this is denoted as dy

def SLM_calc(cp_x, cp_y, lvp_x, lvp_y, rvp_x, rvp_y, S, b, Vinf, alpha, rho):
    """
    This is our Simple Lattice Method Solver
    The inputs as above are as follows
    CP_x, CP_y, these are the coordinates of our control points. Each one should be a 4x1 array
    LVP_x, LVP_y, left vortex point
    RVP_x, RVP_y, right vortex point
    S = area of wing
    b = span of wing (from left wing tip to right wing tip)
    The above inputs depend only on geometry of the wing

    Vinf = freestream flow or speed of aircraft
    alpha = desired angle of attack calculation (this needs to be in radians)
    rho = density of air at prescribed altitude
    """

    DW_star = np.zeros((4,4), float)
    DW_port = np.zeros((4,4), float)

    S = S
    b = b
    Vinf = Vinf
    alpha = alpha 
    rho = rho

    # Typically, when plotting our x coordinate and y coordinates go on their respective axis. Here we need to reverse the axis so that

    LVP_Ys = -1*LVP_Y
    RVP_Ys = -1*RVP_Y

    # Generally, to describe this method, we are going to use the coordinates from the starboard side of the wing, and calculate their contribution at each panel. Then we will add the contributions
    # from the port side of the wing and solve a system of equations. 

    for i in range(0, 4): # i represents control panels (m) , j means other panels and their vortices (n)

            VL_main =   ((RVP_X[j] - LVP_X[j])*(CP_X[i] - LVP_X[j]) + (RVP_Y[j] - LVP_Y[j])*(CP_Y[i] - LVP_Y[j]))/(np.sqrt(( CP_X[i] - LVP_X[j])**2 + ( CP_Y[i] - LVP_Y[j])**2))

            DW_star[i, j] = (Cent * (VL_main+VR_main)) + LV + RV

    # Port Side of Wing

def TrapezoidalWing(b, S, root):
    # b is the span of our wing
    # S is the area of our wing
    # root is the root chord length, we've been given these values in Project 6 and Project 7 Statement

    # First we need a variable for the span of our wing
    span = np.linspace(-b/2, b/2, 200)

    # Then we would like to calculate the chord length of our wing tip
    tip = (2 * S) / b - root

    m = ((root/2) - (tip/2))/ (b/2)
    x = (root/2) - abs(m*span)

    chord = 2 *  x

    return span, chord

span, chord = TrapezoidalWing(48, 235, 8.48)

def EllipticalWing(b, S):
    # b is the span of our wing
    # root is the root chord length, we've been given these values in Project 6 and Project 7 Statement
    croot = (4 * S) / (np.pi * b)

    # First we need a variable for the span of our wing
    span = np.linspace(-b/2, b/2, 101)

    # Then we need to calculate the chord of our wing
    chord = 2 *  (croot/2) * np.sqrt(1 - ((span)/(b/2))**2)

    return span, chord

span, chord = EllipticalWing(48, 235)

Our next step is to calculate the Effective angle of attack $\alpha_{eff}$, our circulation, and washout w of each point on our planforms. Each of these values is closely related for a finite wing. The process to calculate circulation is typically very involved, and requires an iterative process. Rather than have you implement this code yourself, we have provided the circulation data per unit span on Canvas. Lets start by unpacking and loading this data. This is the first of a few plots that we need, but we can take a moment to examine the results from the above plot. 0 span is essentially the wing root. What our plot is telling us is that the circulation about our wing is a maximum at the root of the wing (where the chord is longest and there are no wingtips) and decreases as we move out to the wing tips. The trapezoidal wing has a higher circulation at the root whereas the elliptical wing starts to produce more circulation at about the half way point of the span.

A few things you should consider at this point are: we performed this analysis for a given area S, both the trapezoidal wing planform and the elliptical wing planform produce similar amounts of circulation. One change between the planforms, we did have to reduce the root chord of the elliptic wing in order to maintain the same area S for both wings. From our circulation data above, we can also calculate the value of sectional lift, or the lift per unit span at different points on the wing.

Effective and Induced Angle of Attack¶

Now, we'll start working on our effective angle of attack and induced angle of attack. As a reminder, the effective angle of attack is a result of downwash or washout from the wing tips. This washout causes a slightly differnt angle of attack at different sites of the wing. The equation for effective angle of attack is as follows:

$$\alpha_{eff} = \alpha - \alpha_{i}$$

So we have our angle of attack $\alpha$ and we have an induced angle of attack $\alpha_{i}$ that results from high pressure air on the bottom of the wing escaping to the low pressure side. So, in order to calculate our effective angle of attack, we'll need to calculate the induced angle of attack $\alpha_{i}$. This value can be calculated from the circulation distribution. In the code below you'll need to convert the $V_{\infty}$ to ft/sec.

# Here we need to calculate the derivative of circulation with respect to span.

for i in range(0, nT-1):
    dGammaT[i] = (gT[i+1] - gT[i])/(sT[i+1] - sT[i])
    dGammaE[i] = (gE[i+1] - gE[i])/(sE[i+1] - sE[i])

# Now we need to sum the circulation effects by spanwise location:
for i in range(0, nT):

    integT = np.zeros(nT)
    integE = np.zeros(nT)

    dy_T = sT[1] - sT[0]
    xi_T = sT + dy_T/2

    dy_E = sE[1] - sE[0]
    xi_E = sE + dy_E/2


    for j in range(0, 100):
        integT[j] = dGammaT[j] / (sT[i] - xi_T[j]) 
        integE[j] = dGammaE[j] / (sE[i] - xi_E[j])
    
    J_T = np.trapz(integT[:-1], xi_T[:-1])
    J_E = np.trapz(integE[:-1], xi_E[:-1])


    # Now that we have calculated J, we can calculate our induced angle of attack 

    ai_T[i] = (1/(4*np.pi*Vinf) * J_T) 
    ai_E[i] = (1/(4*np.pi*Vinf) * J_E) 

ai_T[0] = 2*ai_T[1] - ai_T[2]
ai_T[-1] = 2*ai_T[-2] - ai_T[-3]

ai_E[0] = 2*ai_E[1] - ai_E[2]

Downwash Calculation¶

Out next step is to calculate the downwash affecting our wing at different points along the span. Downwash is directly related to our circulation data above, as we took the derivative of the circulation in an effort to calculate the induced angle of attack. Now that we have our induced angle of attack, we can use this value, in combination with our Vinf or freestream speed in order to calculate the downwash distribution over the span of our wing.

The diagram above shows the relationship that we used to calculate our effective angle of attack. This diagram also provides us with the information to calculate our downwash w. We can do this pretty simply using the following equation

$$ W(y) = - V_{\infty} * \alpha_{i}(y) $$

Now that we have our equations and our $\alpha_{i}$ we can calculate and plot the downwash as a function of our wing span. Let do this calculaton and then plot the results. Similar to the above plot for effective angle of attack, implement the above equation and then plot the downwash for both planforms on the same plot.

In [ ]:

Here, we can stop to discuss some of the spanwise characteristics we've found so far. The above two plots we've created are very similar to each other. Our trapezoidal wing has a larger chord value at the wing root than our elliptical wing, due to this, we have a very large downwash magnitude near the root for our trapezoidal wing, and this downwash decreases towards the tips of the wing. For our elliptical planform, the downwash is relatively constant at the root moving outward, but drops in magnitude near the tips of the wing.

Our effective angles of attack are slightly different for each planform. Our effective angle of attack for the trapezoidal wing is a minimum at the root of the wing and steadily increases approaching our base angle of attack of 7 degrees. However, at the tips of the wing, the effective angle of attack drops in magnitude. In other words, the tips of the trapezoidal wing are at a lower angle of attack than further in on the wing. This means that the region of the wing near the tips will stall before the root does, and the stall will slowly creep inward toward the root of the wing as the angle of attack increases. The elliptic wing in comparison is mostly constant and will stall at the tips first, having a minimal effect on the wing. This also means that the wing will stall all at once, rather than gradually.

Sectional Lift / Lift per Unit Span¶

Finally, we should calculate the sectional lift of the wing. We can do this by determining the effective angle of attack at each point on the wing, and then making a simple calculation for total lift. You've been provided with a lift polar on canvas that you can use to calculate the Coefficient of lift for different values of $\alpha_{eff}$. The steps you should take to implement this code are as follows:

  • Step through every point of your effective angle of attack. Remember that this variable changes as we travel along the length / span of our wing. (For loop)
  • Determine the coefficient of lift for each point of our wing, this can be done by interpolating the data from our lift polar and finding the coefficient of lift at the current $\alpha_{eff}$.
  • After finding the coefficient of lift at $\alpha_{eff}$ , plug it into the following equation: $$ L = 0.5 * \rho * V_{\infty}^2 * c * C_{l}$$ c in the above equation stands for the chord at the point where you are calculating the lift.
  • Do this process twice, once for the trapezoidal wing and once for the elliptical wing. The two wings will have different $\alpha_{eff}$ and different chord c along their span

You should notice that the circulation and the sectional lift have the same trends as these quantities are directly proportional.

Problem 3 - Wing Planform Performance Effects¶

3D Performance Effects¶

For this problem we'll be plotting lift curves and drag polars for both of our wing planforms. We can start with the 2D planform data from our p51d polar. Plot this data to get started on our lift curve. Problem 2 gave us the circulation for both the elliptical and trapezoidal planforms. Similar to how we used the circulation to calculate the sectional lift, we can also calculate the 3D coefficient of lift for both planforms. We only have the circulation for $\alpha$ = 7, and so we'll need to determine the circulation at every angle of attack where we would like to determine the lift. We can start to do this using an iterative process.

You have been given the code that we implemented earlier and it has been turned into a function for you, along with a new function to iterate your circulation distribution. Remember that you are creating the following 3 plots:

  • Lift curve with 2D lift, elliptical planform lift, and trapezoidal planform lift (3 lines of data)
  • Drag polar with 2D drag coefficient, elliptical drag coefficient - broken into viscous and inviscid components and total elliptical drag coefficient (4 lines of data )
  • Drag polar with 2D drag coefficient, total elliptical drag coefficient, and total trapezoidal drag coefficient

The 2D values will come from the P51d polar.

The Circ Iteration function given in the code block below is incomplete, and you'll need to implement the calculation of the coefficient of lift, viscous drag coefficient, and inviscid drag coefficient.

The equations you'll need to implement in the CircIteration() function are as follows:

  • For the coefficient of lift: $$C_{L} = \frac{2}{V_{\infty} S}\int_{-b}^{b}\Gamma dx$$
  • The CircIteration() function gives you the value of $\Gamma$ and dx.
  • For the inviscid coefficient of drag: $$C_{Di} = \frac{2}{V_{\infty} S}\int_{-b}^{b}\Gamma sin(\alpha_{i})dx$$

  • The equation above is basically the same as that of the coefficient of lift, but you'll need to change your "integration function" to include the sin of the induced angle of attack $\alpha_{i}$

  • For the viscous coefficient of drag: $C_{Dv}$ is calculated for you.

  • Provide a brief explanation of how $C_{Dv}$ is being calculated according to the below code.

Finally, the code below runs for a single angle of attack, you will need to create a for loop that steps through all of the angles of attack (from 0 to ~25), and runs the code repeatedly to generate our desired lift curve. Once you have created the for loop, each iteration will return/output $C_{L}, C_{Di}$ and $C_{Dv}$ for a single angle of attack. Write some code to capture each of these values and add it to an array. Then plot those results to achieve the 3 plots mentioned above.

S = 235
Vinf = 513.3333
rho = 0.0011
def AoA_Calculation(gamma, span, alpha):
    # First, we'll need a variable for integration later/
    
    #
    nT = len(gT)

    dGamma = np.zeros(nT)
    ai_new = np.zeros(nT)
    ae_new = np.zeros(nT)
    # Here we need to calculate the derivative of circulation with respect to span.
    gamma[0], gamma[-1] = 0, 0

    for i in range(0, nT-1):
        dGamma[i] = (gamma[i+1] - gamma[i])/(span[i+1] - span[i])

    # Now we need to sum the circulation effects by spanwise location:
    for i in range(0, nT):

        integ = np.zeros(nT)

        dy = span[1] - span[0]
        xi = span + dy/2


        for j in range(0, 100):
            integ[j] = dGamma[j] / (span[i] - xi[j]) 

    
        J = np.trapz(integ[:-1], xi[:-1])

        # Now that we have calculated J, we can calculate our induced angle of attack 
        ai_new[i] = 1/(4*np.pi*Vinf) * J

    ai_new[0] = 2*ai_new[1] - ai_new[2]
    ai_new[-1] = 2*ai_new[-2] - ai_new[-3]


    for i in range(0, 101):
        ae_new[i] = alpha - (ai_new[i] * (180/np.pi))

    return ae_new, ai_new


def CircIteration(Gam, span, chord, alpha):
    R = 0
    Vinf = 513.33333
    S = 235 
    
    damping=0.15
    max_iter = 800
    max_res = 1e-4

    new_Gamma = np.zeros(len(Gam))
    Cl_holder= np.zeros(len(Gam))
    dv = np.zeros(len(Gam))

    filename = 'p51d.polar.dat'
    a, Cl_iter, Cd_iter, A, B, C, D = np.loadtxt(filename, skiprows = 12, unpack = True)

    root = round(len(chord)/2)
    # We always need to start with an initial circulation calculation or guess:
    # We start by assuming that our circulation for the wing is an elliptic distribution, based on the chord

    #Initial root circulation guess (elliptic)
    Gam0 = np.pi * chord[root]  / (1 + np.pi * chord[root]/2)


    b = max(span) - min(span)

    #Initial circulation distribution (elliptic)
    new_Gamma = Gam0 * np.sqrt(1 - (2* span / b)**2)
    #new_Gamma[0], new_Gamma[-1] = 0, 0 
    #new_Gamma = Gam

    iter = 1
    res = max_res+1
    j  = 0
    while iter < max_iter and j < 3:
        #CALC NEW CIRCULATION DITRIBUTION
        
        ae, ai = AoA_Calculation(new_Gamma, span, alpha)

        old_Gamma = new_Gamma
        n = len(ae)

        for i in range(0,n):
            Cl_holder[i] = np.interp(ae[i], a, Cl_iter)
            new_Gamma[i] = 0.5 * Vinf * chord[i] * Cl_holder[i]

        #CALC RESIDUAL (difference between current and prev solution)
        R = new_Gamma - old_Gamma
        R = R[5:-5] / old_Gamma[5:-5]

        res = max(abs(R)) #check convergence along entire wing
        # res = abs(R[self.iroot]) #only check root circulation convergence

        #stop iteration when residual has been less than maxres for 5 iters
        if res < max_res:
            j += 1
            # j = 5 #skip the 5 steps after residual

        #SAVE NEW CIRCULATION DISTRIBUTION (use SUR)
        new_Gamma = old_Gamma + damping * (new_Gamma - old_Gamma)


        #increment iteration count
        iter += 1

    fin_iter = iter - 1 #save final iteration count

    # Calculating Lift and Drag
    indices = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(1, 100, 101)]

    # integration function
    f = new_Gamma[indices]

    # integration variable
    dx = span[indices]

    f = 
    coeff_Di = 

    qinf = 0.5*rho* (Vinf**2)

    for i in range(0, n):
        CDv = np.interp(ae[i], a, Cd_iter)
        dv[i] = CDv * qinf * chord[i]
    
    D = np.trapz(dv, x = span)
    coeff_Dv = D / (qinf * S)


    return coeff_L, coeff_Di, coeff_Dv

Problem 4 - Washout and Stall Analysis¶

For this problem we'll be analyzing and comparing a twisted and untwisted wing, to see how it affects the performance of the aircraft close to stall.

Our first step should be to figure out where stall will occur. We plotted our lift curve for the 2D lift conditions, and we can use this to calculate the location of maximum lift and thus the area/angle of attack where stall occurs. Let's reload our polar data and find the stall location. In order to do this, find the angle of attack that corresponds to 2D stall. You've been given the circulation at 0 degrees that can be used to calculate the effective angle of attack. Plot the effective angle of attack over the span of the wing. Then, apply twist to the wing. Wingtwist of 3 degrees means that the airfoil is twisted downward linearly starting from 0 degrees of twist at the root of the wing, and then increasing linearly across the span to 3 degrees of twist at the tip of the wing. You can accomplish this using a linspace.

You've also been provided with the circulation at the stall condition, repeat this process close to stall and apply twist to the wing. Plot both the twisted and untwisted wing and see how they compare close to stall.

def AoA_Calculation(gamma, span, alpha):
    # First, we'll need a variable for integration later/
    
    #
    nT = len(gT)
    Vinf = 513.333333

    dGamma = np.zeros(nT)
    ai_new = np.zeros(nT)
    ae_new = np.zeros(nT)
    # Here we need to calculate the derivative of circulation with respect to span.
    gamma[0], gamma[-1] = 0, 0

    for i in range(0, nT-1):
        dGamma[i] = (gamma[i+1] - gamma[i])/(span[i+1] - span[i])

    # Now we need to sum the circulation effects by spanwise location:
    for i in range(0, nT):

        integ = np.zeros(nT)

        dy = span[1] - span[0]
        xi = span + dy/2

        for j in range(0, 100):
            integ[j] = dGamma[j] / (span[i] - xi[j]) 

    
        J = np.trapz(integ[:-1], xi[:-1])

        # Now that we have calculated J, we can calculate our induced angle of attack 
        ai_new[i] = 1/(4*np.pi*Vinf) * J

    ai_new[0] = 2*ai_new[1] - ai_new[2]
    ai_new[-1] = 2*ai_new[-2] - ai_new[-3]


    for i in range(0, 101):
        ae_new[i] = alpha - (ai_new[i] * (180/np.pi))

    coeff = np.polyfit(span, ae_new, 25)
    p = np.poly1d(coeff)
    ae_fin = p(span)

    return ae_fin, ai_new
